The char residues of the fabrics after cone calorimetry tests were analyzed through SEM, Raman spectra, XPS and XRD. Fig. S6a displayed the digital photographs and SEM images of all the fabrics after burning. Apparently, the C/L was completely destroyed by burning, and a small amount of white ash was left behind. MXene-C/L was burned to retain relatively intact char residue. In contrast, MXene@CDG-C/L and MXene@CDM-C/L only underwent curling and shrinkage after burning, retaining the original morphology of fabric. The SEM images also confirmed that the char residues of C/L and MXene-C/L underwent severe shrinkage, while the char residues of MXene@CDG-C/L and MXene@CDM-C/L were dense and full, with a relatively intact fiber structure. The Raman spectra in Fig. S6b-d showed that the char residues of MXene-C/L, MXene@CDM-C/L and MXene@CDG-C/L all contained two major peaks, D (about 1360 cm−1) and G (about 1580 cm−1) [42]. The integral area ratios (ID
                           /IG
                           ) of the D and G peaks for MXene-C/L, MXene@CDM-C/L and MXene@CDG-C/L were 2.19, 1.98 and 1.44, respectively, which implied that the graphitization of the char residues of MXene@CDM-C/L and MXene@CDG-C/L were higher than that of MXene-C/L.
